weather.text: ay : Mostly sunny, with a high of 83. Wind SE 15-20, with gusts to 30 mph.  Friday : Rain and thunderstorms overnight and into the morning delayed tee times three hours from 6:50 a.m. until 9:50 a.m. with the course receiving 1.71 rain. Improving conditions in the afternoon. Partly cloudy with a high of 83. Wind SSW 15-20 mph with gusts of 30 mph. Play was suspended due to darkness at 7:55 p.m. with 68 players yet to complete the second round.  Saturday : The second round resumed at 7:30 a.m. and concluded at 10 a.m. Mostly sunny with a high of 72. Wind W 20-25 mph, with gusts to 30 mph.  Sunday : Sunny, with a high of 73. Wind W 12-18, gusting to 25 mph.

notes:
Beginning the final round two strokes back, Brian Harman birdied the 71st and 72nd holes to claim his second career PGA TOUR win in his 172nd career PGA TOUR start at the age of 30 years, 3 months, 18 days. Sealed with a 28'4 birdie putt on 18, Harman won by a stroke over Dustin Johnson and Pat Perez.   
   
 For the first time in history of the tournament, the Wells Fargo Championship was not played at Quail Hollow Club in Charlotte, N.C. With the playing of the 2017 PGA Championship at Quail Hollow in August, the Wells Fargo Championship made a one-year stop at Eagle Point Golf Club in Wilmington, N.C.   
   
   Brian Harman, who won the 2014 John Deere Classic, became the sixth left-handed player to capture multiple wins on the PGA TOUR. He also became the first left-hander to win the Wells Fargo Championship.   
   
   Brian Harman became the 10th player in the 15-year history of the Wells Fargo Championship to come from behind in the final round to win.   David Toms (2003), Jim Furyk (2006), Anthony Kim (2008), J.B. Holmes (2014)and Rory McIlroy (2015)were 54-hole leaders who managed to convert for the win.   
   
 FedExCup leader and World No. 1 Dustin Johnson made the 36-hole cut on the number at 1-over 145, before posting back-to-back 5-under 67s in rounds three and four to finish T2 with Pat Perez at 9-under 279. Johnson sank a 15-foot putt for birdie on the 72nd hole to take the clubhouse lead. At the time, co-leader Jon Rahm was on the 15th hole.   
   
   Jon Rahm, who needed an eagle at the par-5 18th hole in the final round to force sudden death, could manage only par for a 1-under 71 and 8-under 280 total(4th). The fourth-place finish marked his sixth top-10 in his last eight PGA TOUR starts.   
   
 Three players entered the field in the top 10 in the FedExCup: Dustin Johnson (1), Jon Rahm (4)and Pat Perez (7). They each finished inside the top four.   
   
   Patrick Reed, who led by a stroke after 54 holes at 8-under 208, struggled in round four, posting a 3-over 75 to finish T12.
